<TITLE> Banks lead Europe stocks down 1.3% to day's low </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European equities shed 1.3 percent on Tuesday, reversing part of the previous day's 2 percent jump, as banks topped the losers' list after Credit Suisse and Barclays reported further write-downs. The DJ Stoxx bank sector index lost 1.5 percent, as shares in Credit Suisse tumbled 9 percent, Barclays shed 1.4 percent and UBS gave up 1.4 percent. By 0916 GMT, the pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index was down 1.25 percent at 1,318.36 -- the day's low. The index has fallen 12 percent so far this year, hit by US recession worries and a slump in the banking sector -- awash with losses lined to a credit crunch. Around European markets, London's FTSE 100 fell 0.8 percent, Paris's CAC-40 lost 0.9 percent and Frankfurt's DAX closed 0.7 perce
